A source inside the meeting confided that it ended being a surgical analysis of Tangatanga and Kieleweke, and, in the end, Mr Kang’ata was tasked to report to the President that all was not well on the ground. 

He was instructed to tell Mr Kenyatta that Mt Kenya was complaining of “being forced into unpalatable political formations, was reeling under policy-driven business hardships and that, generally, the President had become a stranger to them hence rebellion against him and his administration was at its peak.” 

In the meeting, Mr Kang’ata was also put on his defence over his association with the Kieleweke faction of Jubilee Party. 



