Mr Kang’ata confirmed that their meeting was stormy and “as a Jubilee diehard loyal to President Uhuru Kenyatta, I saw it wise to collect that intelligence and compile it and bring it to the attention of my party and its leader.” 

While the Kang’ata letter is dated December 30, a day before the meeting, it is believed that it is after the New Year’s Eve meeting that the letter was actually written, before it hit media headlines on January 3, causing a storm in President Kenyatta’s Mt Kenya backyard. 

The letter, which Mr Kang’ata sent to the Jubilee Party leader through secretary-general Raphael Tuju, has stirred Kenya’s political landscape and put at risk the senator’s plum job in the House. 

The letter has also rattled President Kenyatta’s partners in the ‘Handshake’, ODM, with some of its officials saying the implication of the letter was so huge and “there is more than meets the eye”, according to ODM national treasurer Timothy Bosire — a turn of events that now threatens the peaceful co-existence of the coalition partners. 



