Consensus driven process 

One of the notable angling of Mr Kang’ata’s letter is its advocacy for two pet lines that the Dr Ruto has been pushing in BBI debate — a consensus driven process with multiple referendum questions — hence casting the senator as a man plotting too hard instead of expressly announcing that he was rejoining Tangatanga that he all along belonged to until after 2017 elections when he joined Kieleweke. 

The letter hints at BBI being unpopular in Mt Kenya, with Mr Kang’ata employing ‘scientific’ justifications to his deduction that in every 10 people, six oppose, two support and two had no stand. 

Continuing supporting it in its current form, he added, is tantamount to pinning himself “permanently in the pillar of the shame of the spectacular defeat.” 

The letter was also copied to the majority leaders in both Senate and the National Assembly, with the reasons behind BBI’s alleged unpopularity being the perception that it was a Kieleweke and Mr Odinga’s project that seeks to burden the taxpayer more in supporting a bloated government and that even president’s allies were being marginalised in campaigning for the draft ahead of intended referendum. 



